<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · Cleaning is not optional</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Commercial ice machines require regular cleaning. The math is stark.</h2>

    <p>Industry standard is <strong>2 to 4 cleanings per year</strong> depending on water quality and usage volume. Higher for hard water areas (parts of LA, Orange County, Inland Empire). Higher for high-volume operations (busy bars, hotels, hospitals). Lower only if water filtration is exceptional.</p>

    <p>Why most operators learn this the hard way: they skip cleaning to save $200 to $340 per service, then need a $1,500 to $3,000 evaporator replacement when scale destroys the evaporator at year 3 to 5 instead of the 10 to 15 years it should last. The math is stark: cleaning is the mathematically dominant economic strategy. We're saying it directly because most appliance shops won't.</p>

    <p>We do scheduled cleaning service for commercial ice machines across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside counties. All major brands. <strong>Hoshizaki KM-Edge</strong> (with H-Guard Plus antimicrobial coating that extends but doesn't eliminate cleaning need), <strong>Manitowoc Indigo NXT</strong> (with AlphaSan + LuminIce II antimicrobial systems), <strong>Scotsman Prodigy ELITE</strong>, <strong>Ice-O-Matic ICE series</strong>, <strong>Follett medical-grade</strong>, <strong>Cornelius dispensers</strong>. Every brand needs cleaning. The features just slow biological growth, they don't eliminate scale formation from minerals in water.</p>

    <p>BHGS #A49573. EPA 608 Universal certified. BHGS Licensed #A49573. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 WHY CLEANING MATTERS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · What cleaning prevents</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Three problems regular cleaning prevents.</h2>

    <div class="problem-block">
      <h3>Problem 1: Mineral scale on evaporator</h3>
      <p>Calcium and magnesium in water (especially LA hard water) build on evaporator surfaces. Scale insulates the evaporator. An insulated evaporator freezes ice slower. Slow freeze equals production drops 20 to 40%. Continued scale eventually destroys the evaporator entirely.</p>
      <p><strong>The economic math:</strong></p>
      <ul class="bullet-list">
        <li>Routine cleaning: $200 to $340 per service, 2 to 4 times per year equals $400 to $1,360 annually.</li>
        <li>Scale-destroyed evaporator replacement: $1,500 to $3,000.</li>
        <li>Year 3 to 5 evaporator failure on neglected machine vs year 10 to 15 on properly cleaned machine equals 5 to 10 extra years of service life.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Cleaning pays for itself many times over. This is not a sales pitch, it's math.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="problem-block">
      <h3>Problem 2: Bacterial / yeast / mold growth</h3>
      <p>Ice machines are warm, wet, and dark, a perfect microbial environment. A Vermont University study found the average untouched commercial ice machine had higher bacterial counts than toilet seats. Health inspectors take swab samples on commercial ice machines as routine inspection.</p>
      <p>Bacterial growth means health code violations. Yeast and mold mean ice taste and odor problems means customer complaints.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="problem-block">
      <h3>Problem 3: Slime in water lines</h3>
      <p>Biological film forms in water inlet lines. Causes water inlet valve failures (slime jams the diaphragm), harvest cycle issues (water flow restrictions), and reduced ice production. Cleaning the water lines as part of cleaning service prevents this.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 STANDARD PROCEDURE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Standard cleaning procedure</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we actually do during a cleaning service call.</h2>

    <ol class="proc-list">
      <li><strong>Pre-service diagnostic.</strong> Visual inspection. Check production rate vs nameplate. Note any operational issues. If repair is also needed, we identify it now and quote separately.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain and empty.</strong> Drain the unit completely. Remove all ice from bin. Disconnect power for safety.</li>
      <li><strong>Apply brand-spec cleaner.</strong> Different brands use different cleaners, this matters:
        <ul class="sub-list">
          <li><strong>Hoshizaki:</strong> Hoshizaki Scale Away (brand-spec)</li>
          <li><strong>Manitowoc:</strong> Manitowoc Cleen Ice (brand-spec)</li>
          <li><strong>Scotsman / Ice-O-Matic / generic:</strong> Nu-Calgon Ice Machine Cleaner (industry standard nickel-safe)</li>
        </ul>
        Using the wrong cleaner can damage evaporator coatings. We use brand-spec cleaners.
      </li>
      <li><strong>Run cleaning cycle.</strong> Most modern machines (Manitowoc Indigo NXT, Hoshizaki KM-Edge, Scotsman Prodigy ELITE) have built-in cleaning programs. Older machines: manual circulation through the evaporator.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain and rinse.</strong> Thorough rinsing. No cleaner residue allowed in food-contact surfaces.</li>
      <li><strong>Sanitize.</strong> Apply food-safe sanitizer (US Ice Machine Sanitizer or similar). Sanitization is a separate step from cleaning, different chemistry, different purpose.</li>
      <li><strong>Water filter replacement.</strong> Filter replacement timing depends on filter system:
        <ul class="sub-list">
          <li><strong>3M Cuno</strong> filters (common Manitowoc): 6-month typical</li>
          <li><strong>Pentair Everpure</strong> (common Hoshizaki, Scotsman): 6-month typical</li>
          <li><strong>OptiPure</strong> (premium installations): 6 to 12 month</li>
          <li><strong>Manitowoc K-Series</strong> (Manitowoc-specific): per Manitowoc spec timing</li>
        </ul>
        Hard water areas or high-volume operations: 3-month filter replacement.
      </li>
      <li><strong>Restart, verify, discard first batch.</strong> Restart machine. Monitor harvest cycles. Always discard the first batch of ice even after thorough rinsing, minor cleaner residue makes ice unsafe.</li>
      <li><strong>Service documentation.</strong> We document service for your health inspection records: date, technician, cleaner used, sanitizer used, filter replaced, water test results if applicable.</li>
    </ol>

    <p><strong>Total time:</strong> 90 minutes to 2.5 hours typical depending on machine size plus cleaning frequency history (heavily neglected machines take longer).</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL CLEANING STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Real cleaning service stories</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Composite stories from the route.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Five cleaning service jobs from the past 90 days. Models, symptoms, work performed, time, total. Names omitted; the technical scenarios are typical of what we see weekly.</p>

    <div class="story-grid">
      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Bar in West Hollywood · Manitowoc Indigo NXT IY-0454A · last cleaning 18 months ago, R-404A</h3>
        <p>Friday 8 PM, no ice, bar service stopped. Diagnosed: scale buildup on evaporator. Drained, applied Manitowoc Cleen Ice, ran cleaning cycle, sanitized, replaced Pentair Everpure 4FC-S filter (overdue). Production restored. Total: $120 emergency diagnostic + $280 cleaning + $160 filter = $560. Bar continued service 90 minutes after our arrival. Owner committed to a quarterly cleaning contract going forward.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Coffee shop in Pasadena · Hoshizaki KM-340MAJ undercounter · never cleaned in 3 years</h3>
        <p>Owner thought "automatic cleaning cycle" was sufficient (it's not, automatic cycles flush water but don't remove scale). Scale was heavy on the evaporator, ice production at 40% of nameplate. Major cleaning required (took 3 hours due to neglect): drained, mechanical scrub of evaporator (heavy scale required mechanical removal in addition to chemical), full Scale Away treatment, multiple rinses, sanitization, replaced water filter. Production restored to 95% nameplate. Total: $120 + $480 (extended cleaning) + $160 filter = $760. Owner now on quarterly schedule.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Hospital in Pasadena · Manitowoc R-Series RNS-0820A nugget · quarterly contract for 4 years</h3>
        <p>Preventive cleaning. Standard procedure, 90 minutes. Total: $280 service. Hospital procurement appreciates predictable maintenance budget. 4-year-old machine still operating at 98% nameplate.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Restaurant chain in Beverly Hills · 3 Manitowoc Indigo NXT machines (mixed sizes IY/IB)</h3>
        <p>Quarterly fleet cleaning coordinated through the corporate facility manager. All 3 machines cleaned plus filter replacements in a single visit. Total: $720 (3 × $240 fleet pricing) + $480 filters = $1,200. Corporate appreciated the single-dispatch fleet coordination.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Sushi restaurant on Sawtelle · Hoshizaki F-450MAH-C flake ice · quarterly cleaning contract</h3>
        <p>Flake machines accumulate scale slightly differently from cube (scale in the auger drum). Standard cleaning procedure adapted for flake architecture. Total: $280. 7-year-old flake machine still operating at nameplate.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 HONEST SCOPE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Honest scope</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we service, what we don't.</h2>

    <p><strong>We service:</strong> all major brands and ice types. Cube (Hoshizaki KM-Edge, Manitowoc Indigo NXT, Scotsman Prodigy ELITE, Ice-O-Matic), flake (Hoshizaki F-Series, Manitowoc, Scotsman flake), nugget (Scotsman Brilliance, Hoshizaki Sliver Nugget, Manitowoc R-Series), self-serve dispensers (Cornelius, Hoshizaki, Manitowoc, Follett). We use brand-spec cleaners. Replace water filters as part of service. Document for health inspection records.</p>

    <p><strong>We don't do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>New ice machine installation (specialty installer trade)</li>
      <li>Major repair work under the cleaning umbrella (we'll diagnose and quote separately if repairs needed)</li>
      <li>Ice bin standalone cleaning without machine service</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Quarterly contract pricing:</strong> Annual contracts (4 cleanings + filter replacements) lower per-cleaning cost. Multi-machine accounts get fleet pricing. Monthly billing available for chain and hospitality accounts.</p>
  </div>
</section>

